# Screen Ui (`screen-ui.mdc`)

# Feature Screen UI — Decomposed Pattern

Reference: `src/Feature/Quest/screens/ChapterStartScreen/`.

Complex screens (multiple UI phases, overlays, loading/error/ready) must **not** hold business logic or Redux in JSX. The screen is a thin `switch` over a ready **UIModel**; orchestration lives in a hook; display rules live in pure mappers.

Simple screens (single layout, 1–2 selectors) may stay flat — see `ui-components.mdc`.

---

## Folder Structure

```
Feature/<Feature>/screens/<ScreenName>/
├── <ScreenName>.tsx                     # Container: switch on UIModel.kind, no logic
├── hooks/
│   └── use<ScreenName>.ts               # Redux, navigation, side-effects, handlers
├── models/
│   └── <screen>UIModel.ts               # Discriminated union + Actions interface
├── mappers/
│   ├── <screen>Mapper.ts                # Domain/Redux → UIModel (assembly)
│   └── resolve<Screen>ViewState.ts      # Pure: which UI phase to show
├── constants/
│   └── <screen>Constants.ts             # Copy, magic strings, testIDs
├── components/
│   ├── <Screen><Phase>View.tsx          # Presentational view for one phase
│   └── <Screen><Shared>.tsx             # Shared in-screen layout (backdrop, footer)
└── __tests__/
    ├── resolve<Screen>ViewState.test.ts
    └── <screen>Mapper.test.ts
```

**Naming conventions:**
- View components — `View` suffix (`ChapterStartReadyView`)
- Hook — `use<ScreenName>`
- UIModel file — `<screen>UIModel.ts`
- View state resolver — `resolve<ScreenName>ViewState.ts`
- UIModel mapper — `<screen>Mapper.ts`

---

## Layer Responsibilities

| Layer | File | Does | Does not |
|-------|------|------|----------|
| **Screen** | `<ScreenName>.tsx` | `useHook()` → `switch (uiModel.kind)` → `<*View />` | Redux, dispatch, useEffect, business rules |
| **Container hook** | `hooks/use*.ts` | selectors, dispatch thunks, navigation, local UI state (transient errors), callbacks | JSX, StyleSheet, Domain → UI field mapping |
| **View state resolver** | `mappers/resolve*.ts` | Pure: which `ViewKind` from Redux flags | I/O, hooks, React |
| **UIModel mapper** | `mappers/*Mapper.ts` | Pure: assemble `UIModel`, palette subset, nested UI structs | dispatch, navigation |
| **UIModel** | `models/*UIModel.ts` | Presentation-only types; `as const` discriminant | Domain, DTO, Redux types |
| **View** | `components/*View.tsx` | Layout from props; palette/chapter/message | Redux, Service, thunks |
| **Constants** | `constants/*.ts` | User-facing strings, loader steps, testIDs | Logic |

Business rules live in **Service / thunks / pure resolvers**, not in views or the screen container.

---

## UIModel — Discriminated Union

```ts
// models/<screen>UIModel.ts
export const MyScreenViewKind = {
  Loading: 'loading',
  Error: 'error',
  Ready: 'ready',
} as const;

export type MyScreenViewKind =
  (typeof MyScreenViewKind)[keyof typeof MyScreenViewKind];

export type MyScreenUIModel =
  | { kind: typeof MyScreenViewKind.Loading; palette: MyScreenPaletteUIModel }
  | { kind: typeof MyScreenViewKind.Ready; palette: MyScreenPaletteUIModel; data: MyScreenDataUIModel }
  | { kind: typeof MyScreenViewKind.Error; palette: MyScreenPaletteUIModel; message: string }

/** Actions — separate from UIModel */
export interface MyScreenActions {
  onConfirm: () => void;
  onBack: () => void;
  onRetry: () => void;
}
```

**UIModel rules:**
- Only fields needed for rendering: strings, numbers, palette subset, nested UI structs.
- **No** Domain types, Redux state, or navigation.
- Palette is a **subset** of the shared palette (`Pick<StoryStyleUIPalette, 'mainTextColor' | 'accentColor'>` or a dedicated interface). Mapping palette → subset belongs in `*Mapper.ts`.
- Discriminant `kind` — `as const` object, **not** `enum`.
- Actions / callbacks — **separate** interface, not part of the union.

---

## Screen Container

```tsx
// <ScreenName>.tsx — switch only
export function MyScreen() {
  const { uiModel, actions } = useMyScreen();

  switch (uiModel.kind) {
    case MyScreenViewKind.Loading:
      return <MyScreenLoadingView palette={uiModel.palette} />;
    case MyScreenViewKind.Ready:
      return (
        <MyScreenReadyView
          palette={uiModel.palette}
          data={uiModel.data}
          onConfirm={actions.onConfirm}
          onBack={actions.onBack}
        />
      );
    case MyScreenViewKind.Error:
      return (
        <MyScreenErrorView
          palette={uiModel.palette}
          message={uiModel.message}
          onRetry={actions.onRetry}
        />
      );
  }
}
```

- Named export.
- No `useAppSelector`, `useEffect`, or `StyleSheet` in the screen file.
- Switch must be exhaustive — TypeScript must cover every `ViewKind`.

---

## Container Hook

```ts
export function useMyScreen(): {
  uiModel: MyScreenUIModel;
  actions: MyScreenActions;
} {
  // 1. Route params and navigation
  const { someId } = useRoute<MyScreenRouteProp>().params;
  const navigation = useNavigation();

  // 2. useAppSelector — read Redux state only
  const isLoading = useAppSelector(selectIsLoading);
  const data = useAppSelector(selectData);
  const loadError = useAppSelector(selectLoadError);

  // 3. useEffect — dispatch thunks (init, fetch)
  // When deps change (e.g. someId) — list them explicitly in the deps array
  useEffect(() => {
    dispatch(loadData({ someId }));
  }, [someId]);

  // 4. useCallback — handlers (navigate, retry, dismiss)
  const handleConfirm = useCallback(() => {
    navigation.navigate('NextScreen');
  }, [navigation]);

  const handleRetry = useCallback(() => {
    dispatch(loadData({ someId }));
  }, [someId]);

  // 5. Mapping — single call at the end
  // useMemo only if the mapper sorts/filters large arrays or builds heavy nested structs.
  // For a typical pure mapper — not required.
  const uiModel = mapMyScreenUIModel({ isLoading, data, loadError });

  return {
    uiModel,
    actions: {
      onConfirm: handleConfirm,
      onBack: navigation.goBack,
      onRetry: handleRetry,
    },
  };
}
```

**Hook rules:**
- Hook **delegates** UI phase selection to `resolve*ViewState`, never computes it inline.
- Local UI state — transient display state only; do not duplicate Redux domain.
- `navigate()` — only inside the hook via `useNavigation()`; never pass navigation into views or store it on `actions`.
- For changing `useEffect` deps — list them explicitly and handle race conditions when needed.

---

## Pure Mappers

### View State Resolver
Defines phase priority. **If order matters** — test every branch:

```ts
// mappers/resolveMyScreenViewState.ts
export interface ResolveMyScreenViewStateParams {
  isLoading: boolean;
  hasData: boolean;
  loadError: string | null;
}

export function resolveMyScreenViewState(params: ResolveMyScreenViewStateParams): MyScreenViewKind {
  if (params.isLoading || !params.hasData) return MyScreenViewKind.Loading;
  if (params.loadError) return MyScreenViewKind.Error;
  return MyScreenViewKind.Ready;
}
```

### UIModel Mapper
Assembles the union from the resolver result, with explicit fallback branches:

```ts
// mappers/myScreenMapper.ts
export function mapMyScreenUIModel(input: MapMyScreenUIModelParams): MyScreenUIModel {
  const palette = mapPaletteToMyScreen(input.storyStyle ?? null);
  const kind = resolveMyScreenViewState(input);

  switch (kind) {
    case MyScreenViewKind.Loading:
      return { kind, palette };

    case MyScreenViewKind.Error:
      return { kind, palette, message: input.loadError ?? FALLBACK_ERROR_MESSAGE };

    case MyScreenViewKind.Ready:
      if (!input.data) {
        // Fallback: resolver returned Ready but data is missing — safe error
        return { kind: MyScreenViewKind.Error, palette, message: DATA_NOT_FOUND_MESSAGE };
      }
      return { kind, palette, data: mapDataToUIModel(input.data) };
  }
}
```

**Palette subset:**
```ts
// Option 1 — Pick from shared palette
type MyScreenPaletteUIModel = Pick<StoryStyleUIPalette, 'mainTextColor' | 'accentColor' | 'backgroundColor'>;

// Option 2 — dedicated interface (preferred for larger subsets)
interface MyScreenPaletteUIModel {
  mainTextColor: string;
  accentColor: string;
  backgroundColor: string;
}

// Mapping — in *Mapper.ts
function mapPaletteToMyScreen(style: StoryStyle | null): MyScreenPaletteUIModel { … }
```

---

## Presentational Views

```tsx
// components/MyScreenReadyView.tsx

interface MyScreenReadyViewProps {
  palette: MyScreenPaletteUIModel;
  data: MyScreenDataUIModel;
  onConfirm: () => void;
  onBack: () => void;
  testID?: string;
}

/** @component */
export function MyScreenReadyView({ palette, data, onConfirm, onBack, testID }: MyScreenReadyViewProps) {
  return (
    <MyScreenBackdrop palette={palette} testID={testID}>
      <Text style={{ color: palette.mainTextColor }}>{data.title}</Text>
      <MyScreenFooter
        palette={palette}
        primaryLabel={CONFIRM_BUTTON_LABEL}
        onPrimary={onConfirm}
        onBack={onBack}
      />
    </MyScreenBackdrop>
  );
}
```

**View rules:**
- Props — UIModel types + callbacks. No Domain types.
- Shared in-screen layout (`MyScreenBackdrop`, `MyScreenFooter`) — in the screen's `components/`, not global `UIComponents/`.
- Styling: `Font`, `Margin`/`Padding` from `theme.ts`; colors from `palette` or `DesignSystemColors` — see `ui-components.mdc`.
- `testID` — via constants or optional prop; do not hardcode strings in JSX.
- `@component` JSDoc on every view file.

---

## Error Boundaries

Screens with loading/error phases handle **expected** errors via UIModel (`Error` phase).

For **unexpected** runtime throws — place an Error Boundary **above** the screen container, at navigator or root layout level. The screen container is not an Error Boundary.

```tsx
// Navigator level — not in the screen file itself
<ErrorBoundary fallback={<GlobalErrorFallback />}>
  <Stack.Screen name="MyScreen" component={MyScreen} />
</ErrorBoundary>
```

---

## Tests

| What to test | File | Priority |
|--------------|------|----------|
| Phase order and branches | `resolve*ViewState.test.ts` | **Required** |
| UIModel assembly, fallbacks, palette mapping | `*Mapper.test.ts` | **Required** |
| Hook orchestration | separate test if pure tests are insufficient | As needed |
| Screen container / Views | snapshot or RTL | As needed |

```ts
// resolve*ViewState.test.ts
describe('resolveMyScreenViewState', () => {
  it('returns Loading when isLoading=true regardless of other flags', () => {
    expect(resolveMyScreenViewState({ isLoading: true, hasData: true, loadError: null }))
      .toBe(MyScreenViewKind.Loading);
  });

  it('returns Error when loadError present and not loading', () => {
    expect(resolveMyScreenViewState({ isLoading: false, hasData: true, loadError: 'Network error' }))
      .toBe(MyScreenViewKind.Error);
  });

  it('returns Ready when loaded and no error', () => {
    expect(resolveMyScreenViewState({ isLoading: false, hasData: true, loadError: null }))
      .toBe(MyScreenViewKind.Ready);
  });
});

// *Mapper.test.ts
describe('mapMyScreenUIModel', () => {
  it('falls back to Error when kind=Ready but data is missing', () => {
    const result = mapMyScreenUIModel({ isLoading: false, hasData: true, loadError: null, data: null, storyStyle: null });
    expect(result.kind).toBe(MyScreenViewKind.Error);
  });

  it('maps palette subset correctly', () => {
    const result = mapMyScreenUIModel({ …validInput });
    expect(result.palette).toMatchObject({ mainTextColor: expect.any(String) });
  });
});
```

---

## Anti-Patterns

```tsx
// ❌ Business logic and Redux in screen
export function MyScreen() {
  const phase = useAppSelector(s => s.contentUpdate.phase);
  if (phase === 'downloading') return <Loading />;
  dispatch(initScreen()); // side-effect in render
}

// ✅ Hook + UIModel + switch
const { uiModel, actions } = useMyScreen();
switch (uiModel.kind) { … }
```

```tsx
// ❌ Domain types in view props
<ReadyView chapter={chapterDomain} story={storyDomain} />

// ✅ UIModel subset
<ReadyView data={uiModel.data} palette={uiModel.palette} />
```

```ts
// ❌ ViewKind computed inline in hook (50 lines of conditions)
const kind = contentUpdate.phase === 'idle' && !updateNeeded ? 'ready' : …;

// ✅ Delegate to pure resolver
const kind = resolveMyScreenViewState({ isLoading, hasData, loadError });
```

```ts
// ❌ Actions inside UIModel union
| { kind: 'ready'; onConfirm: () => void }

// ✅ Separate interface
return { uiModel, actions };
```

```tsx
// ❌ Service/Repository called from view
useEffect(() => { MyService.loadData() }, []);

// ✅ Thunk from container hook
dispatch(loadData({ someId }));
```

```ts
// ❌ Full StoryStyleUIPalette passed to view
| { kind: 'ready'; palette: StoryStyleUIPalette }

// ✅ Only needed fields — palette subset
| { kind: 'ready'; palette: MyScreenPaletteUIModel }
```

```ts
// ❌ navigation passed to view or stored on actions
actions: { navigation }

// ✅ navigation used only inside hook
const handleConfirm = useCallback(() => navigation.navigate('Next'), [navigation]);
actions: { onConfirm: handleConfirm }
```

---

## When to Apply

| Screen | Pattern |
|--------|---------|
| Multiple phases (loading / error / ready / overlay) | **Decomposed** (this rule) |
| Complex mapping from multiple Redux slices | **Decomposed** |
| Simple list / form / single layout / 1–2 selectors | Flat screen — `ui-components.mdc` is enough |

When refactoring a legacy screen: create a `<ScreenName>/` folder and extract hook + UIModel + views incrementally. The screen file stays the route entry point throughout the refactor.

